Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The number of countries and territories reporting confirmed cases of COVID-19 to WHO remains at 215. In the 24 hours since the last WHO update:

- The Americas region reported 54.5% of the global newly reported cases and 65.3% of newly reported deaths for this 24-hour period, maintaining its dominance as the most severely affected region, having reported more than 10.1 million cases. The USA reported 35.6% of cases (55 318), followed by Brazil 34.2% (53 139), Colombia 7.7% (11 996), Peru 5.0% (7785), Argentina 4.8% (7513), Mexico 4.2% (6590), and Chile 1.4% (2154).

- The European region reported 11.0% of the global newly reported cases and 6.9% of the newly confirmed deaths globally. Russia reported 16.5% (5212) of the regional newly confirmed cases, followed by Spain 14.3 % (4507), Kazakhstan 14.1% (4413), France 6.0% (2181), Israel 6.9% (1672), Ukraine 4.7% (1489), Romania 4.4% (1379), Turkey 3.7% (1185), Germany 3.5% (1122), the UK 2.7% (871), Poland 2.6% (809), Uzbekistan 2.1% (650), and Kyrgyzstan 3.5% (425).

- The Eastern Mediterranean region reported 4.4% of the global newly reported cases and 5.4% of global newly reported fatalities. Iraq reported 27.3% (3461) of the regional newly reported cases, followed by Iran 19.4% (2450), Saudi Arabia 12.4% (1567), Morocco 8.0% (1018), Pakistan 6.5% (824), Kuwait 5.4% (682), Palestinian Authority 4.1% (514), Oman 2.7% (354), Lebanon 2.2% (279), and Libya 1.6% (199). Cases are increasing in Iraq and Morocco. This region remains highly active, with multiple countries still in a surge mode.

- The African region reported 4.2% of the global newly reported cases and 5.9% of newly reported fatalities. South Africa reported 60.8% (7292) of the newly reported cases in the region in the past 24 hours, followed by Kenya 6.1% (727), Ethiopia 4.6% (552), Algeria 4.4% (529), Ghana 3.8% (455), Nigeria 3.6% (443), and Madagascar 1.5% (182). While South Africa is the dominant country in the region, it has halved its daily case count in the past few days.

- The Western Pacific region reported 2.1% of the global newly reported cases and 0.56% of global deaths. The Philippines reported 56.3% (3294) of the newly reported cases in the region, followed by Japan 27.7% (1624), Australia 7.0% (410), Singapore 4.1% (242), China 2.1% (120), South Korea 0.73% (43), and Viet Nam 0.66% (39). Japan and Australia continue to increase in transmission.

- The South East Asia region reported 23.7% of the global newly reported cases and 15.7% of global deaths. India reported 91.23% (61 537) of newly reported cases in the region, followed by Bangladesh 4.2% (2851), and Indonesia 3.6% (2473). India continues to be the driving force of the dominance of this region.

Impression: The overall picture is basically the same. The ordering of the regions has the Americas having the highest disease load and newly confirmed cases on a daily basis followed by the South East Asia region, then Europe followed by the Eastern Mediterranean, followed by the Africa region and the Western Pacific region representing the lowest daily caseload of all the regions. While regional proportions may not reflect this, most of the regions have countries that have resurgences of cases associated with lifting of restrictions.

Figure 2. The epidemic curve of confirmed COVID-19 cases by date of report and WHO region, 30 Dec 2019 through 7 Aug 2020, at the source URL above is an excellent visual representation of the epidemic as described in the above text. - Mod.UBA]

